- Be able to talk to people - Be able to talk to people. Be able to talk, to people, specifically - Ideally you should have some kind of education in your background - Ideally you should have something to demonstrate that you are a committed person - Ideally you should be able to demonstrate that you can work well in a team - Don't fucking smell. Jesus. - Ideally you should be able to solve a few whiteboard style problems - Be honest, that's the most important thing, don't bullshit your way around something. Highlight things you know confidently. Also highlight when you're not sure and don't know. - Figure out how eye contact works then do it - Don't be afraid of asking questions - Don't forget you are interviewing them as much as they are interviewing you All of those things are far more important than "I sometimes code discord bots on my weekends"...

The dumbest bug I've ever seen and solved in person. User starts the program. Video starts playing. The video can be 30 minutes long, for example. You crash the program (intentionally) and the media should start back where it stopped. This client wanted the media to start back 120 seconds prior to the crash time. The program was starting back between 120 seconds or over by some random amount. Meaning, sometimes it got it perfectly correct and sometimes it was messing up by an amount of seconds. You could reproduce it working to the second 10 times in a row then sometimes it could be 17 seconds out just randomly. The first thing we had to do is hack the element to track all of the time events so that we could see where the hell exactly it was starting back at. Turns out most of the time it was not starting back correctly it just looked like it was because the media was in a different language. On the real burnout can occur to anyone and time is definitely not the only factor. It can happen to people who code 30 hours a week in a job they absolutely hate with a passion, and it might miss people who are programming 80 hours per week. The reality is at the end of the day, if you want to avoid programmer burnout, here are some points: - If you are in a job, be defensive about programming at a home, do it max 30 mins per day. There's a lot of the world to experience. 40 hours per week plus an additional 30 mins of your free time? You're definitely going to zap yourself with the burnout gun sooner or later, remember you'll want to be able to program for about 40 years as a job... don't tire yourself out too early. The ideal amount of work is that which can be sustained for decades - If a project reallly does not interest you, don't start it, and don't finish it either. Don't code when you really don't want to. You will hate it. - Avoid overtime at work like the plague. Leave o...

I'd just like to interject for a moment. What you're referring to as C++, is in fact, C/C++, or as I've recently taken to calling it, C plus C++. C++ is not a language unto itself, but rather another free component of a fully functioning C language made useful by the C standard libs, shell utilities and vital system components comprising a full compiler infrastructure as defined by ANSI. Many computer users run a modified version of the C language every day, without realizing it. Through a peculiar turn of events, the version of C which is widely used today is often called "C++", and many of its users are not aware that it is basically the C language, developed by Dennis Ritchie & Bell Labs. There really is a C++, and these people are using it, but it is just a part of the language they use. C++ is the parser: the program in the compiler that translates the source's code into machine language. The parser is an essential part of a compiler, but useless by itself; it can only function ...

Matrices in Julia are easy and fun!
matrix = [1 2 3; 4 5 6] #you must have a space between elements, and a semicolon between the rows #= Creates a 2x3 matrix that looks like this: 1 2 3 4 5 6 =#
Useful matrix operations: hcat()- horizontal concatenation, it stacks 2 or more matrices horizontally.
matrix = [1 2 3; 4 5 6] hcat(matrix, [5;5]) #remember our matrix is 2x3 #= so now this is a 2x4 matrix. 2 -4 -3 5 4 -2 1 5 You'll get an error if the matrices don't have the same number of rows. =#
`vcat()- vertical concatenation, this operation stacks 2 or more matrices on top of each other.`julia matrix = [1 2 3; 4 5 6] #2x3 matrix vcat(matrix, [0, 0, 0]) #= 3x3 matrix 1 2 3 4 5 6 0 0 0 Cool, right? But you'll get an error if the two matrices don't have the same number of columns.=#``
